{{for|the municipality in Chile|Cunco, Chile}}
The '''Cuncos''' (kunkunche) are a sedentary native Chilean people, belonging to the southern group of [[Mapuche]] peoples, and that inhabited the coasts of [[Chile]] from [[Valdivia, Chile|Valdivia]] to the [[Chacao Channel]], including the inhabitants of the northern portion of [[Chiloé Island]] and the bordering islands. They spoke the [[Mapudungun]] language, common to all the Mapuche peoples. They had a developed [[agriculture]], specializing in the culture of [[potato]]es and [[maize]] along with [[fishing]] and [[hunting]]. In addition they used sturdy wooden boats ([[dalca]]s) with which they crossed their coastal waters in search of fish and seafood.
[[File:Pueblos indigenas de Chile.svg|thumb|center|700px|Distribution of the pre-Hispanic people of Chile]]
