{{Azerbaijanis}}
'''Iranian Azerbaijanis''' ({{lang-az|ایران آذربایجانلیلاری – İran azərbaycanlıları}}), also known as '''Iranian Azeris''', '''Iranian Turks''', '''Persian Turks''', '''Azeri Turks''', '''Azerbaijani Turks'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mrWRAAAAIAAJ&q=azeri+turks&dq=azeri+turks&hl=en&ei=PWidTbnKAs-58gOrhJzQBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=book-thumbnail&resnum=10&ved=0CGcQ6wEwCQ|title=Soviet Asian ethnic frontiers|first1=William O.|last1=MacCagg|first2=Brian D.|last2=Silver|date=10 May 1979|publisher=Pergamon Press|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ogp8AHZ3ZN4C&pg=PA160&dq=azeri+turks&hl=en&ei=YGqdTY_wC4iq8AObiN2-BA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=book-thumbnail&resnum=3&ved=0CDwQ6wEwAjgU#v=onepage&q=azeri+turks&f=true|title=Iran: Political Development in a Changing Society|first=Leonard|last=Binder|date=10 May 1962|publisher=University of California Press|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yAgGHnENHjoC&pg=PA200&dq=azeri+turks&hl=en&ei=HX9qTv-_I83D8QOd9-gr&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC8Q6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=azeri+turks&f=false|title=World Regional Geography|first=Joseph J.|last=Hobbs|date=13 March 2008|publisher=Cengage Learning|via=Google Books}}</ref> or '''Persian Azerbaijanis''',<ref>"Richard Nelson Frye, "Persia", Allen & Unwin, 1968.  pp 17:
"in World War II, contact with brethren in Soviet Azerbaijan likewise were not overly cordial since the Persian Azeris are {{sic|?|commited|expected=committed}} to Iranian culture and consider their destiny to be with the Persians rather than with other Turks"</ref><ref>Tadeusz Swietochowski, "Russian Azerbaijan, 1905-1920: The Shaping of a National Identity in a Muslim Community", Cambridge University Press, 2004.  pg 192:  [https://books.google.com/books?id=cozSOSsv7ZsC&pg=PA192&dq=%22Persian+Azerbaijanis%22&hl=en&ei=FL39TaGDGYLJgQfkw8DuCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22Persian%20Azerbaijanis%22&f=false] Excerpt "...identity with the Persian Azerbaijanis"</ref> are [[Iran]]ians of [[Azerbaijanis|Azerbaijani]] ethnicity who may speak the [[Azerbaijani language]] as their first language.

Azerbaijanis are the second largest ethnic group in the nation.<ref name="books.google.nl">Brenda Shaffer. [https://books.google.nl/books?id=uEOd-cDWVwQC&pg=PA229&dq=azerbaijanis+second+largest+ethnicity+iran&hl=nl&sa=X&ei=kt90VZnYIoKS7AbLu4Bg&ved=0CEIQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=azerbaijanis%20second%20largest%20ethnicity%20iran&f=false ''The Limits of Culture: Islam and Foreign Policy'' MIT Press, 2006] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115184407/https://books.google.nl/books?id=uEOd-cDWVwQC&pg=PA229&dq=azerbaijanis+second+largest+ethnicity+iran&hl=nl&sa=X&ei=kt90VZnYIoKS7AbLu4Bg&ved=0CEIQ6AEwBA |date=2018-01-15 }} {{ISBN|0262195291}} p 229</ref> Furthermore, the largest population of ethnic Azerbaijanis in the world live in Iran, far outnumbering those in the neighbouring [[Azerbaijan Republic]].

Iranian Azerbaijanis are mainly found in and are native to the [[Iranian Azerbaijan]] region including provinces of  ([[East Azerbaijan]], [[Ardabil Province|Ardabil]], [[Zanjan Province|Zanjan]], [[West Azerbaijan]])<ref name="countrystudies.us">{{cite web|url=http://countrystudies.us/iran/41.htm|title=Iran - Turkic-speaking Groups|author=|date=|website=countrystudies.us|deadurl=no|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20110819093627/http://countrystudies.us/iran/41.htm|archivedate=2011-08-19|df=}}</ref><ref name="Encyclopedia of the Stateless Nations">[https://books.google.com/books?id=Zu5GpDby9H0C&pg=PA1765&dq=majority+of+the+population+of+East+Azarbaijan+and+a+majority+of+West+Azarbaijan.&hl=en&sa=X&ei=NOFNT-jKI8ibOsChwLYC&ved=0CFkQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=majority%20of%20the%20population%20of%20East%20Azarbaijan%20and%20a%20majority%20of%20West%20Azarbaijan.&f=false Encyclopedia of the Stateless Nations: S-Z] Volume 4 of Encyclopedia of the Stateless Nations: Ethnic and National Groups Around the World, James Minahan, {{ISBN|0-313-31617-1}}, {{ISBN|978-0-313-31617-3}}, Author James Minahan, Publisher Greenwood Publishing Group, 2002, {{ISBN|0-313-32384-4}}, {{ISBN|978-0-313-32384-3}}, Length 2241 pages</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ciaonet.org/pbei/winep/policy_2006/2006_1146/index.html|title=CIAO|author=|date=|website=www.ciaonet.org|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071201195641/http://www.ciaonet.org/pbei/winep/policy_2006/2006_1146/index.html|archivedate=2007-12-01|df=}}</ref> and in smaller numbers, in other provinces such as [[Kurdistan Province|Kurdistan]], [[Qazvin Province|Qazvin]], [[Hamadan Province|Hamadan]], [[Gilan Province|Gilan]], [[Markazi Province|Markazi]] and [[Kermanshah Province|Kermanshah]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Michael Knüppel |first=E. |title=TURKIC LANGUAGES OF PERSIA |encyclopedia=[[Encyclopædia Iranica]] |accessdate=2013-09-19 |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/turkic-languages-overview |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053354/http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/turkic-languages-overview |archivedate=2013-09-21 |df= }}</ref> Iranian Azerbaijanis also constitute a significant minority in [[Tehran]], [[Karaj]] and other regions.<ref name="Library of Congress Iran 1">Library of Congress, "Country Studies"- Iran: Azarbaijanis  {{cite web |url=http://countrystudies.us/iran/42.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-03-30 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20110704043703/http://countrystudies.us/iran/42.htm |archivedate=2011-07-04 |df= }} accessed March 2011.</ref><ref name="Library of Congress Iran 2">"Chapter 2 - The Society and Its Environment: People and Languages: Turkic-speaking Groups: Azarbaijanis" in ''A Country Study: Iran'' Library of Congress Country Studies, [http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/irtoc.html#ir0052 Table of Contents] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313185348/http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/irtoc.html |date=2007-03-13 }}, last accessed 19 November 2008</ref><ref>[http://dspace.khazar.org/jspui/handle/123456789/183 THE TURKISH LANGUAGE IN IRAN] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005022717/http://dspace.khazar.org/jspui/handle/123456789/183 |date=2013-10-05 }} By Ahmed KASRAVI, latimeria: Prof. Dr. Evan Siegal, Journal of Azerbaijani Studies, 1998, Vol. 1, No 2, [6], Khazar University Press, {{ISSN|1027-3875}}</ref>

==Demographics==
Azerbaijanis comprise the largest minority ethnic group in Iran.<ref name="books.google.nl" /> Apart from [[Iranian Azerbaijan]] (provinces of [[West Azerbaijan]], [[East Azerbaijan]], [[Ardabil Province|Ardabil]] and [[Zanjan Province|Zanjan]]), indigenous Azeri population is found in large numbers in four provinces: [[Hamadan Province|Hamadan]] (58% Azeri, as well as closely related groups such as [[Afshar tribe|Afshar]], Gharehgozloo, [[Shahsevan]], and [[Baharlu (ethnic group)|Baharloo]]<ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite web|url=http://hamedan-hm.ir/fa/showpages.aspx?mid=NDg=&spi=Mw==|title=فرمانداري همدان|author=|date=|website=hamedan-hm.ir|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101133427/http://hamedan-hm.ir/fa/showpages.aspx?mid=NDg=&spi=Mw==|archivedate=2013-11-01|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/turkic-languages-overview|title=TURKIC LANGUAGES OF PERSIA:  AN OVERVIEW – Encyclopaedia Iranica|first=|last=electricpulp.com|date=|website=www.iranicaonline.org|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053354/http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/turkic-languages-overview|archivedate=2013-09-21|df=}}</ref>),<ref name="Iran-Azerbaijanis" /> [[Qazvin Province|Qazvin]] (52.2% Azerbaijani),<ref>Plan review and assess the country's culture indicators (indicators Ghyrsbty) {report}: [[Qazvin Province]] / General Council of the Order of the Executive Director is responsible for planning and policy: Mansoor Vaezi; run company experienced researchers Us - {{ISBN|978-600-6627-53-3}} * Publication Status: Tehran - Institute Press book, published in 1391 * appearance: 268 p: table (the color), diagrams (colored part)</ref> [[Markazi Province|Markazi]] (20.8% Azerbaijani)<ref>National Bibliography Number: 2887000/plan review and assess the country's culture indicators (indicators Ghyrsbty) {report}: [[Markazi Province]] / General Council of the Order of the Executive Director is responsible for planning and policy: Mansoor Vaezi; run company experienced researchers Us - {{ISBN|978-600-6627-63-2}} * Publication Status: Tehran - Institute Press book, published in 1391 * appearance: 276 p: table (the color), diagrams (colored part)</ref> and [[Kurdistan Province|Kurdistan]].<ref name="kordestan">"Kordestan." [[Encyclopædia Britannica]]. 2009. Encyclopædia Britannica Online. 5 Apr. 2009</ref><ref>[http://en.ostan-kd.ir/Default.aspx?TabID=51 Government of Kurdistan Province] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510122447/http://en.ostan-kd.ir/Default.aspx?TabID=51 |date=2013-05-10 }} People and culture '''(English)'''</ref> Azeri-populated parts of Markazi include [[Komijan County|Komijan]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://markazi.irib.ir/about-us/about-ostan-markazi/audio-descripcostan/785-- |title=Komijan County |publisher=[[IRIB]] Aftab Channel |year=2009 |accessdate=August 19, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140121143525/http://markazi.irib.ir/about-us/about-ostan-markazi/audio-descripcostan/785-- |archivedate=January 21, 2014 |df= }}</ref> [[Khondab County|Khondab]],<ref>{{cite news|url= http://markazi.irib.ir/index.php/about-us/about-ostan-markazi/audio-descripcostan/726|title= Khondab County|publisher= [[IRIB]] Aftab Channel|year= 2008|accessdate= August 19, 2013|deadurl= no|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130831203000/http://markazi.irib.ir/index.php/about-us/about-ostan-markazi/audio-descripcostan/726|archivedate= August 31, 2013|df= }}</ref> [[Saveh County|Saveh]],<ref name="Markazi Province" /><ref>{{cite news|url= http://markazi.irib.ir/index.php/about-us/about-ostan-markazi/audio-descripcostan/746---|title= Saveh County|publisher= [[IRIB]] Aftab Channel|date= August 2013|accessdate= August 19, 2013|deadurl= no|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130901130931/http://markazi.irib.ir/index.php/about-us/about-ostan-markazi/audio-descripcostan/746---|archivedate= September 1, 2013|df= }}</ref> [[Zarandieh County|Zarandieh]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://markazi.farhang.gov.ir/fa/introduction/offices/officezarandiyeh |title=Zarandieh County |publisher=[[Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance (Iran)|Office of Culture and Islamic Guidance]], [[Markazi Province]] |date= |accessdate=August 19, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103034653/http://markazi.farhang.gov.ir/fa/introduction/offices/officezarandiyeh |archivedate=November 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref> [[Shazand County|Shazand]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://markazi.farhang.gov.ir/fa/introduction/offices/officeshazand |title=Shazand County |publisher=[[Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance (Iran)|Office of Culture and Islamic Guidance]] Markazi Province |date= |accessdate=August 19, 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228102018/http://markazi.farhang.gov.ir/fa/introduction/offices/officeshazand |archivedate=December 28, 2013 |df= }}</ref> and [[Farahan County|Farahan]].<ref name="Markazi Province">{{cite news |url=http://markazi.farhang.gov.ir/fa/moarefi |title=Markazi Province |publisher=[[Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance (Iran)|Office of Culture and Islamic Guidance]], [[Markazi Province]] |date= |accessdate=August 18, 2012 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130225045957/http://markazi.farhang.gov.ir/fa/moarefi |archivedate=February 25, 2013 |df= }}</ref> In Kurdistan, Azeris are mainly found in villages around [[Qorveh]].<ref name="kordestan"/>

Azeris have also immigrated and resettled in large numbers in Central Iran, mainly [[Tehran]],<ref name="R. Tapper">{{cite news|url= http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/azerbaijan-vi|title= AZERBAIJAN vi. Population and its Occupations and Culture|publisher= [[Encyclopædia Iranica]]|date= August 18, 2011|accessdate= August 18, 2012|deadurl= no|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121002163724/http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/azerbaijan-vi|archivedate= October 2, 2012|df= }}</ref> where they constitute 25%<ref name="Tehran">{{cite web |url=http://looklex.com/e.o/teheran.htm |title=Tehran |publisher=[[Looklex Encyclopaedia]] |date= |accessdate=2013-07-04 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130429060418/http://looklex.com/e.o/teheran.htm |archivedate=2013-04-29 |df= }}</ref> — one-third of the population,<ref name="Iran-Azerbaijanis">{{cite news |url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/r?frd/cstdy:@field(DOCID+ir0052) |title=Iran-Azerbaijanis |publisher=[[Library of Congress Country Studies]] |date=December 1987 |accessdate=13 August 2013 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150323105535/http://lcweb2.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/r?frd%2Fcstdy%3A%40field%28DOCID+ir0052%29 |archivedate=23 March 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>National Bibliography Number: 2887741 / plan review and assess the country's culture indicators (indicators Ghyrsbty) {report}: [[Tehran Province]] / General Council of the Order of the Executive Director is responsible for planning and policy: Mansoor Vaezi; run company experienced researchers Us - {{ISBN|978-600-6627-42-7}} * Publication Status: Tehran - Institute Press book, published in 1391 * appearance: 296 p: table (the color), diagrams (colored part)</ref> [[Qum]] (25.8% to 26.6% Azeri)<ref name="R. Tapper" /><ref name="The Council of Public Culture">{{cite news|url=National Bibliography Number: 2890690 / plan review and assess the country's culture indicators (indicators Ghyrsbty) {report}: [[Tehran]] 199066,