===Religion===

The majority of Azeris are followers of [[Shia Islam]]. Azeris commemorate Shia holy days (ten first days of the holy month of Muharram) at least with the same intensity as other Iranians. In metropolitan cities with mixed ethnic composition, such as [[Tehran]], Azeris are thought to be more intense in their expression of religious ritual than their [[Persian people|Persian]] counterparts.<ref>R. Khanam, Encycl. Ethnography Of Middle-East And Central Asia, 2005, vol. I, p. 80</ref> However, Azeris are less inclined to [[Islamism]]. This is evident by the fact that just before revolution Azeris followed either [[Mohammad Kazem Shariatmadari]] or Kho'i, both traditionalist jurists. In contrast, [[Persian people|Persians]] followed more radical [[Ruhollah Khomeini]].{{cn|date=October 2018}}

There is also a small minority of Azeris who practice the [[Bahá'í Faith]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iranpresswatch.org/post/13946/|title=Burial Denied to a Baha'i Citizen in Tabriz - Iran Press Watch|author=|date=26 January 2016|website=iranpresswatch.org|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822051443/http://iranpresswatch.org/post/13946/|archivedate=22 August 2016|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bahai-library.com/curtis_iran_country_study|title=Iran|author=|date=|website=bahai-library.com|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413181053/http://bahai-library.com/curtis_iran_country_study|archivedate=2016-04-13|df=}}</ref> Also in recent years, some Azeris in Iran have begun converting to [[Christianity]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christiantelegraph.com/issue20646.html|title=Three Iranian-Azeri Christians Arrested; Their Fate Unknown|author=|date=|website=www.christiantelegraph.com|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806034606/http://www.christiantelegraph.com/issue20646.html|archivedate=2016-08-06|df=}}</ref> which is strictly prohibited and can result in imprisonment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2009/may/09/iran-christianity-conversion|title=The cost of religious conversion in Iran - Theresa Malinowska|first=Theresa|last=Malinowska|date=9 May 2009|website=the Guardian|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220142203/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/belief/2009/may/09/iran-christianity-conversion|archivedate=20 December 2016|df=}}</ref>

Followers of [[Yarisan]] religion (Goran in the Azeri language) constitute a significant fraction of the population. In some regions [[Yarisan]] followers are sometimes known as Shamlus, a clear reference to the name of Shamlu tribe, which was one of the main constituents of [[Qizilbash]] confederation.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}

