{{redirects here|East Timor languages|other uses|Languages of East Timor}} {{Infobox language family |name=Oirata–Makasai |altname=Eastern Timor |region=[[East Timor]], [[Kisar]] |familycolor=Papuan |fam1=[[Trans–New Guinea]] |fam2=Berau Gulf |fam3=[[West Bomberai languages|West Bomberai]]<ref>[https://sites.google.com/site/newguineaworld/families/trans-new-guinea/berau-gulf/west-bomberai New Guinea World, West Bomberai]</ref> |fam4=[[Timor–Alor–Pantar languages|Timor–Alor–Pantar]] |child1=Oirata–Fataluku |child2=Makasae |glotto=east2520 |glottorefname=East Timor }}
The '''Oirata–Makasai''', or '''Eastern Timor''', languages are a small family of [[Papuan languages]] spoken in eastern [[Timor]] and the neighboring island of [[Kisar]].
==Languages== Mandala ''et al.'' (2011)<ref>Mandala, Halus; Aron Meko Mbete, Ni Made Dhanawaty and Inyo Yis Fernandez. 2011: [http://ojs.unud.ac.id/index.php/eol/article/view/3550/2581 “Phonological Evolution of Oirata and its Genetic Relationship with Non-Austronesian Languages in Timor-Leste”], ''Denpasar: Ejournal Universitas Udayana''.</ref> found that Fataluku and Oirata are closer to each other than they are to Makasai:
*[[Makasai language|Makasai]] (including [[Makalero dialect]]) *Oirata–Fataluku **[[Fataluku language|Fataluku]] ([[Rusenu language|Rusenu]] perhaps belongs here) **[[Oirata language|Oirata]]
Fataluku has high dialect diversity, and may be more than a single language, for example with [[Rusenu language|Rusenu]]. An additional [[Makuv'a language|Makuv'a]] (Lovaea) branch was once assumed for East Timor, but that appears to be a heavily Papuan-influenced Austronesian language.
The fourth Papuan language spoken in East Timor, [[Bunak language|Bunak]], is more distantly related. It is currently unknown if they are closer to each other or to the [[Alor–Pantar languages]]; all are clearly related. They may be closest to the [[West Bomberai languages]] of mainland New Guinea, but this is as yet speculative.<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/1861441/The_historical_relations_of_the_Papuan_languages_of_Timor_and_Kisar]</ref>
==Classification== Ross (2005) reconstructed first- and second-person pronouns for proto–East Timor:<ref>{{Malcolm Ross Pronouns}}</ref>
:{| class=wikitable ! !!proto-ET!!Oirata (object)!!Fataluku!!Makasai |- !1sg |*ani||an-te (ani)||ani||ani |- !2sg |*ai||aa-te/ee-te<ref>''ee-te'' is a polite form</ref> (ee)||e||ai |- !1ex |*ini||in-te (in)||ini||ini |- !1in |*api||ap-te (ap)||afi||fi |- !2pl |*i||ii-te (ii)||i||i |}
Mandala ''et al.'' (2011) reconstruct five vowels, *a, *e, *i, *o, *u, and the following consonants, based on 200 cognate sets:
:{| class="wikitable" ! !Labial !Alveolar !Velar !Glottal |- align="center" ! Nasal | {{IPA|*m}} | {{IPA|*n}} | | |- align="center" ! Occlusive | {{IPA|*p}} | {{IPA|*t}} | {{IPA|*k}} | {{IPA|*ʔ}} |- align="center" ! Fricative | | {{IPA|*s}} | | |- align="center" ! Sonorant | {{IPA|*w}} | {{IPA|*l, *r}} | | |}
<nowiki>*</nowiki>h and *j appear at the level of proto-Oirata–Fataluku.
